\section{Simulation of Plane Wave}\label{T_S_Field_Formulation}\index{FDTD!total/scattered Field}\index{FDTD!plane wave simulation}

		FTDD models of receiving antennas need to use a plane-wave source condition to create an incident electromagnetic wave. In order to simulate a plane wave in a FDTD program, the problem space will be divided up into two regions, namely the total field and scattered field regions. The reasons behind this division are that the propagating plane wave should not interact with the absorbing boundary conditions and the load on the absorbing boundary conditions should be minimized \cite{Sullivan_book_00}. These boundary conditions are not perfect, i.e., a certain portion of the impinging wave reflects back into the problem space. By subtracting the incident field, the amount of radiating field hitting the boundary is minimized, thereby reducing the amount of error. The method for the simulation of plane wave given in \cite{Sullivan_book_00} is detailed in appendix \ref{}.










The problem, like prediction of the performance of an antenna in receiving mode working as an EM field sensor, deal with the plane waves. In order to simulate a plane wave in a FDTD program, the problem space will be divided up into two regions, namely the total field and scattered field regions as shown in the Fig.~\ref{Fig:total_scattered_field}. The reasons behind this division are that the propagating plane wave should not interact with the absorbing boundary conditions and the load on the absorbing boundary conditions should be minimized \cite{Sullivan_book_00}. These boundary conditions are not perfect, i.e., a certain portion of the impinging wave reflects back into the problem space. By subtracting the incident field, the amount of the radiating field hitting the boundary is minimized, thereby reducing the amount of error.

Fig.~\ref{Fig:total_scattered_field} illustrates how this is accomplished. First an auxiliary one-dimensional buffer called the incident array is considered. As this is a one-dimensional array, it is easy to generate a plane wave: a source point is chosen and the incident $E_z$ field is just added at that point. Then a plane wave propagates away in both directions. Since it is a one-dimensional array, the boundary conditions are perfect \cite{Sullivan_book_00}.

